Assuming:

WAN/External Interface = Connected to 192.168.74.0/24 bridge network
External IP = 192.168.74.X
Internal Server IP = 192.168.1.10
Traffic arriving on TCP 80 should be forwarded to 192.168.1.10:8080
Default policy should be DROP
Using iptables
A. Port Forward TCP 80 → 192.168.1.10:8080 and Log Traffic
# Enable IP forwarding
echo 1 > /proc/sys/net/ipv4/ip_forward

# Log incoming HTTP traffic
iptables -t nat -A PREROUTING -p tcp --dport 80 \
-j LOG --log-prefix "HTTP_FORWARD: "

# Forward traffic to internal server port 8080
iptables -t nat -A PREROUTING -p tcp --dport 80 \
-j DNAT --to-destination 192.168.1.10:8080
B. Allow Forwarded Traffic and Related Return Packets
# Allow incoming forwarded traffic
iptables -A FORWARD -p tcp -d 192.168.1.10 --dport 8080 \
-m state --state NEW,ESTABLISHED,RELATED -j ACCEPT

# Allow return traffic
iptables -A FORWARD -p tcp -s 192.168.1.10 --sport 8080 \
-m state --state ESTABLISHED,RELATED -j ACCEPT
Source NAT (MASQUERADE)

Required so responses return through the firewall.

iptables -t nat -A POSTROUTING -o eth0 -j MASQUERADE

Replace eth0 with your WAN interface.

C. Drop Everything Else
iptables -P INPUT DROP
iptables -P FORWARD DROP
iptables -P OUTPUT DROP

Allow established connections:

iptables -A INPUT -m state --state ESTABLISHED,RELATED -j ACCEPT
iptables -A OUTPUT -m state --state ESTABLISHED,RELATED -j ACCEPT
Verify Rules
iptables -L -n -v
iptables -t nat -L -n -v
